{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}London}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid3636049\charrsid16072257 {\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid3636049 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 
\par I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 In Marylebone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Whereabouts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 In High Street, Marylebone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 What was your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 parent\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267  house like
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
Well I think they had two furnished rooms in those days or one then they moved to another place. They always had about two rooms. It was only small, myself and two brothers. I was the eldest. They were business people, they ha
d a business, they acquired a business in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Drury Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 What sort of business was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 It was a hairdressing business and then they had one also in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname 
Street}}Charing Cross Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and then came back bought another business in what is now {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Bulstrode Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, in Hig
h Street, Marylebone. So we were just a bit above the ordinary class you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 How old were you ... When you moved?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Drury Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
? Well I think I was, a little child of about 4 or 5 I should imagine. I may have been a bit older because my brother was born there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 How old were your brothers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
One is six years and one has just passed away so I think he is just about eight years younger than me. They went to school. When we moved they went to a very nice school in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}
Castle Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} connected with St. Martins in the Fields a sort of little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 subsidiary}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
 school something like that where they went a little while
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 You went there too did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Oh yes I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Castle Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 school for some years. Oh yes. And then we moved for quite a number of year
s we were around by Guildford Street and we went to a large school called London school called P.......Terrace which is now been rebuilt. It was bombed during the war and that sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Had you taken many people working for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Oh yes he had quite a few. About }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 five or six}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
 or perhaps more in those days. Yes. Oh he must have had more with three shops. Oh it was in those days yes but we saw quite enough. My mother used to have someone come in - she had a washerwoman in those days. You could get
 them you see in those days. I think you could have got them for about half a crown a day. My mother gave more I think 3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 /}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
6 or something. They gave them their food and they did the whole wash you had them every week or every often we I forget but she always
 had somebody come in and do the rough I think she felt more sorry for the people. You know perhaps one person would give a couple of hours somebody who had not much to eat you know probably hard up. Well you can come in and do a couple of hours do a litt
le bit of work in the morning. You can have your dinner with us and that sort of thing and I think the two or three shillings which was a lot of money in those days. You can't compare them with now it is all out of proportion. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 I know when I went to school w
e went to cookery class and I think you could make a very,very nice dinner for 1/- in those days I'm sure we made a little meal out for a shilling a very nice dinner stew and all that sort of thing. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Potatoes were 4 lb. for 2d. you could go to the big market {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Chapel Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, Islington all sorts of things. You could get things very, very cheap, out of all proportion today.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Did you mother do her own bakery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 No she made her cakes but she didn't bake them. Some of the Sunday dinners would be taken to th
e bakers. Oh yes. I remember that, especially when we had visitors coming. We would get those lovely pieces of beef. Then somebody my father or somebody I couldn't tell you who took them to the bakers with the potatoes, and that sort of a? thing. Dish for
 the Yorkshire pudding I don't know how much he gave I think it was only a couple of coppers. I am not quite certain, that was a lot done in those days that was in my younger days before the 1914 war when of course well things have altered considerably.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Had you a kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Drury Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
? Well there was one large room but it didn't have the sink in it. The sink was on the stairs In those days there wasn't even gas. We were the first people in the business to have the gas then up to be 1st floor. Ther
e was no gas in those days not until the 1890 or 1901 or there wasn't anything like that you see but they rigged up a kitchen there and my mother did quite a lot of cooking and that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 You had a gas stove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Yes, we were the first but 
not a stove, we had a top one with three plates, we didn't have the new mat oven. You see everybody had their ovens in the fire. You see they had fireplaces with ovens in those days dear. Most people cook by that. I don't think we did. My mother had a lar
ge gas.......ring which was put on the same cupboard as the sink and when she cooked her dinner she did all the gravy on top. But other people in the house like I told you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 How many other people were there in that house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 In that house. We had the
 first floor. There were three different families on the second floor. 1 lady, her grandchild, then there were two maiden ladies who had one room and then there was another a widow Mrs? and her daughter. So there were three different families on the secon
d floor. Then on the top floor there was one lady there and in three big rooms there was this family with 12 children. That was in that particular house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 You all shared one sink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 On the staircase yes, and apart from the sink that was in the baseme
nt for washing, that there was only one sink no others. Many other houses, I know friends who lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Charlotte Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 I used to go and stay with them, sometimes there was only one sink on the staircase too. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Lot{\*\xmlclose} of that in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} in those days especially before the first war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 What had you the basement?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
Yes the washhouse the toilet downstairs in the basement. You see it was like two horrible rooms down there, I think some people used to live there some of the down and outs used to live down there.
 I should imagine so. But not in this house where we were. It was a huge basement. One of the rooms was left as a storing place. The landlords who owned the place they had an oil store a real old fashioned oil store and he used to store a lot of his stuff
 in the other part.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 How did you heat water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
Well the water was on the first floor so you had big water cans, galvanised water cans. You couldn't have a bath everyday. You didn't use water like you do now, nobody did in those days. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 
You could wash, none of us children was put to bed dirty mind you, there was a basin when you wanted it because for us it was only up six stairs from our first floor to the sink so it wasn't too bad but other people of course it was very difficult. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 The lady from the thir
d floor used to come down for her huge family and water - you can just imagine what a drudge that must have been. None of the children were dirty mind you, many of them were far cleaner than some of the children today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 You had three rooms then? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15276983\charrsid4274267 One had a range in it?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 In the kitchen, then there was one bedroom. The }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 two}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267  of us children we had the front room with a put}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 up bed. From what I can remember. I don't know whether it was my two brothers or whether it was me and maybe it was me and they wo
re - parents I don't know. I can't quite remember that but of course in those days a lot of children slept in the same room as their parents, all that sort of thing. They had to and these model dwellings that, one of these philanthropists and people like 
t
hat started these model dwelling places and got their own little very tiny little bedrooms, that sort of thing because they were pioneers, that started it you see. From there it has gone on until now you see these vast flats which is very nice indeed but 
I think it has spoilt a lot of community life, the friendliness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 What were the neighbours like round you? You saw them a lot did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Oh yes we lived next to a doctor because we were business people my parents. Dr..... was there he had the whole h
ouse to himself of course he had a large family he had. He had a little trap, we used to see him going out in a little horse and trap in those days right up until the end of the first world war. Yes, oh yes, there were other business people there. We had 
l
ots of friends there, I suppose children had nowhere else to play very much except somebody my parents or somebody would take us over to Lincolns Inn Fields to play there or the little squares but the majority of children of course played in the streets, 
where else was there for us to play. Children didn't have the terrific amount of toys that children have these days. You made your own games and that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 What sort of games did you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Very much the same games as today, hopscotch, sk
ipping and all those sorts of things jumping about, rounders, if you could get the space there was a little court called Broad Court opposite us}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267  lot of children used to play roun}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 d there and there was the Peabody}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
 Trust, was round there, they were also the pioneers well they had their big grounds which kept a lot of their children there you see. That Mr. Peabody did very}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267  very great work for the poor people. You could get a very nice single room for decent people for 5/6d. in those days. I remember a lady wh
o used to come to see us and she was thrilled when she got a little room there. Then there was one sink on each floor in these big buildings. She thought how lovely it was when she came out of her room and to go there and not have to go up and downstairs 
w
here she was before she had one nice room. I think it was 5/6d. or 6/6d. all according to Mr. Peabody, who started the Peabody Trust, which was a very, very great thing in those days. Of course that's all been altered now. I think the majority from what I
 can see now they've all been re-organised, modernized, yes. Lots of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 How far away was your school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
It wasn't very far away. We could just cross over and got knocked down by a bicycle one day and got a good spanking when I got home, for being knocked down, that I do remember. No the school wasn't so far away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 How big was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 It was a big school. Well I don't know, it was a fairly big school. It wasn't quite so big as the school in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Wild Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I don't know whether you have been round to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}
Great Queen Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, that is also a very interesting part. That is the centre of the Free Masons. Huge place there Great Queen Street leads from things was to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Drury Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, very interesting all round there. It has altered so much there, so much. There is a big school still down there that wild Street school. That started as the school board for 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 years ago so that what it was SBL you can still see it is still written up. Outside well of course that absorbed there must be hundreds of children like that my parents didn't like the leader us young there so we went to that smaller school in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Castle Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 which was connected with St. Martins in the Fields which was very nice. We used to go to church in St. Martins in the Fields. It was sort of a Church of England school which was very nice yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Did you enjoy school? Were they strict?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
Oh yes I think well you approach school you had a lot of respect for your teachers to start off with. Well I suppose they were to a point I don't know, I suppose I was
 always afraid of getting trouble, I guess I should have been in more got a bad resort were my parents trouble when I got home, my parents were rather on the strict side with us which I think is a very good thing, I don't care what people say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 What were they strict about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
Oh manners and all that sort of that. You couldn't talk to your parents, you couldn't behave in those days as you do now. We had respect and we had respect for our teachers. Miss Robinson when she came in and if Miss Robinson tha
t's our teachers name looked at us nicely well that made the day for us. If some of the children were naughty well that also upset us nobody wanted Miss Robinson to give you a bad look. You did have respect for your teacher, there is no question about tha
t. The sure we all did. I have heard my daughter some years ago come home and tell us about she went to a very nice Church of England school {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}St. Thomas{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
's in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Wigmore Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Then I got married and moved to Marylebone Lane, that was also a nice part of London
 for many years, we lived there for a long time and she went to a nice church school St. Thomas's which has now been done away, Selfridges Food Store stands on the a delightful Church of England school but I mean she used to come home and tell us of how s
h
e'd spoken to the teachers and it used to horrify me. So I don't know what I should say if I heard some of the talk of the children these days. My grandchild now and again she comes and I hear her talk and I think I don't know it wouldn't have done for us
 
to talk to our teachers like that. We were brought up the environment was different and you had quite a lot more respect for your teacher. We have got this American idea over here so much with education. I know when I have been abroad quite recently, in t
he last few years that children have far more respect for their teachers schooling abroad especially in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} you know or in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}Germany{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to what they've got over in this country, there is still a trace of it abroad but in this country it has got quite to the o
pposite. It is getting so Americanised over here which is appealing very sad indeed. They have no respect for the teachers that we used to have. I don't say we stood in awe of them but I think one should have a little respect for ones elders and that sort
 
of thing and not greet them or meet them on the same footing or hail fellow well met. Then I am considered a square I'm old fashioned I think they have gone too much, I think the younger generation has. I admire young people, it wouldn't do for them to ha
ve the hard life we had but I do think they've gone a little too far too much to the other extreme.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
I can only think how we respected and admired our teachers. Looking back on school, it was very nice and one or two teachers were really very nice; one
 was a Miss Newman, she was so kind and so helpful to me and she was sharp mind you. You had to have respect for her, when she said a thing she meant it and that was that. When one gets older, one appreciates it, I think there should be more of that in th
i
s day and age. It has got too much, it has got too free and easy which is no good which is no good. I think there are still some boarding schools where some children still have a very, very tough time, if you did but know it. Still people talk of the publ
ic school, what took place in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Eton{\*\xmlclose}. I don't know whether you have ever toured {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Eton{\*\xmlclose}
 and those rooms where they had to wash in ice cold water when the water was solid and the bedrooms and things like that, it all wants a little thinking about. Now everything is laid on so much it's all wrong.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 What were your favourite lessons?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
I always liked history. Mathematics I was always rather hopeless, at I loathed English and Shakespeare, I suppose because you see we didn't have it put across like you do now. S
ometimes I listen to schools and now and again and you hear different ways of putting it across, it is quite different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 What was your teaching like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Well I don't know I suppose she did put it across alright. English I didn't like at school. My gr
andchild excels in it. History and Geography were my favourites. The only thing is I've got order I haven't a retentive memory now like I used to have but they were arithmetic I didn't like. I used to ordered, English after I went to a trade school in tho
se days, you see, to learn millinery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Whereabouts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 That was in Queen's Square. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Another part of a lovely bit of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Do you know Southampton Row, West Central of course dear old Imperial Hotel is now pulled down but if you know Hotel Russell wel
l go down there and just on your right is Queens Square, there is the big hospital for Nervous diseases and then there is the Orthopaedic Hospital then there's that's were the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 children\rquote 
s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267  hospital Great Ormond Street. In that corner there it is still there 
called a technical college but in my time when I went in 1914 or 15 that was a trade school for girls and I was taught millinery there. My parents thought I ought to have to learn a trade and I went there for two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 What other things did they teach?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
We had general education which was very nice and we had a very wonderful principal Miss Smythe. I think now looking back she was one of the original suffragettes I think so because in those days I wasn't quite polite enough you didn't have things p
ut across like you do with wireless and television and I have a suspicion that was never nice. I came out quite qualified as a milliner and then they found me a job in Bourne and Hollingsworth where I was for quite some time of course you were quite quali
f
ied. You were taught a trade quite thoroughly and as I say general but of course we had an English mistress there and she was rather on the sharp side and of course and I was hopeless in that same thing and of course we did all sorts of subjects. An art m
i
stress there a Miss Lacy a very old fashioned lady looking back upon on her now. Quite an eccentric person but what a clever person. I am no good at drawing lines but she used to come and draw them and I used to say look it is so easy when you do it, I co
u
ldn't do it of course. You had to learn designing. I had to design hats the art or lines and all that sort of thing. That was quite nice except of course it was spoilt I left 1916 for the war. You see the war was on in 1916 and of course the war was rathe
r
 nasty in those days, you never knew what was happening so it spoilt my life quite a bit. That was a very nice institution and a very wonderful church there that St. Georges church on the corner. It is a very old church. Handle used to play there you know
 and of course that part of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Great Ormond Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and then couldn't Street there, very nice bit of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} but it is all getting so spoilt. All the lovely houses you know are being demolished, of course its old property I do agree but they ought to preserve a few of those old houses in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Great Ormond Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Yes. I like them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
Aren't they nice? I go round there once a year, one afternoon I have an early lunch and I go down there, it is a lovely part because when my daughter was young she attended the Gr
eat Ormond Street hospital for all her little ailments, tonsils all sorts of things, lovely very nice hospital for children. Th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 en there is that Coram}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267  Street there, those gardens where the children used to be left at the Founding Hospital it was a fact I ca
n remember people saying the basket was outside and children were left there, they were taken there they leave children even now for different things. He was a great man that Captain Coram, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Coram Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was named after him. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 He did a lot of work round that 
part and of course it was very heavily residential, Kings Cross Road, Grays Inn Road and Bow Street which leads off Swinton Street, Frederick St and Cromer Street, all those places were very heavily populated, will very, very poor people. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 I don't know how they managed you know. I used to know a woman there Annie Smith, I don't know how I got to know her and she worked as a little assistant in a little haberdashery shop in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Great Queen Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and she got the magnificent sum of 8/- per week.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 They lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Cromer Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 that's right a whole family of 6 or 7, they had a dear little house. I don't know how I got to know her maybe through church. Anyhow when I went there she said would I like to have a cup of tea with us one day and I said I'd love to and Mis
s Smith went there and they were so poor but they were so nice and I although she earned so little she was always making something out of nothing. Those people always making something out of nothing and she never looked poor and yet she was earning so lit
tle and she was saving a little bit for when she got married. Very, very poor. How she managed I don't know, you'd never think it. Those are the people I admire. Looking back I think now that Miss Smith how did she manage, the way she walked from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Great Queen Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Cromer Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 which is quite a tidy walk, quite a nice walk, but then there weren't buses they were horse buses. I can remember the underground them getting on for a half penny. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3281965\charrsid4274267 
I can remember the tram lines from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Theobalds Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to the Embankment was a ha'penny. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Devon{\*\xmlclose}
 not so long ago. Somebody in the railway carriage thought I had made a mistake, I said oh no I had done it so often I used to go to Sunday morning school we used to have a girl to look after us, she'd take us to church and
 then when we come out we used to walk to the top of Great Queen Street get on that thing for a ha'penny to the underground there. I remember it being opened - lovely. You see we used to go to Sunday school in the morning the children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Whereabouts was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 
Well that was off a tiny little court off the Kingsway which is still there which leads into Wild Street, a dear little mission church it belonged to the Holy Trinity, Kingsway and I can remember that little church, with a little mission hall, wh
ite scrubbed floors nice little papers there and the lady who was in charge was a Miss Hanley and her husband was a lay reader and she used to take us teach us and we used to sing' All things bright and beautiful, all the little children and they were all
 poor and all so clean and so nice there at 10 o'clock in the morning. I think one-half part or one-quarter to or something like that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15276983\charrsid4274267 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 very Sunday? Yes. I can remember it so vivid, it impressed me as a little child how clean everything was, all these little children, all poor from around {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Covent Garden{\*\xmlclose}
. Twice a year they would be taken for a little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4339284\charrsid4274267 o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 uting to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4339284\charrsid4274267  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 ? Wood then a little Christmas party. For those children a party was something wonderful in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 My mother would }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4339284\charrsid4274267 later}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267  make a little donatio
n and perhaps send a couple of bob. She didn't want them to think we were in a better position than some of them of course being business people and they were always being asked for help. I wanted to go but my mother said no it's not meant for you and I s
aid I wanted to see other children there. These parties were wonderful for those poor children, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Wild Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, all the little courts around, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}Kemble Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} all from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Covent Garden{\*\xmlclose}
. And so many little children used to come what so impressed me was they all looked so clean. All these baths and weird and wonderful soap, things and all the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4339284\charrsid4274267 paraphernalia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267  you have today, I can see them now lovely clean little mission hall how nice all the children seemed, it seemed nice in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3636049 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Was there a Sunday afternoon school too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12460854 C  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 Yes, Sunday afternoons, what was it, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 0}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 15}}}3 o'clock{\*\xmlclose}
 we used to go there it wasn't far. Children used to go to a lot of Sunday school in those days, there was nothing else for them to do. These days you see like my grandchild, I used to say to 
my daughter why doesn't Josephine go but they go out and couldn't be bothered. The Sunday school is a thing of the past, nobody wants to go and teach all day Sundays, we used to go and very nice it used to be too, very nice indeed. That was a different pl
ace that was really in Holy Trinity, Kingsway at the back of the church itself, where we went to our Sunday afternoon schools, very nice indeed. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4339284\charrsid4274267 
Then some time later in life on we got attached to the London Medical mission which was in Endell Street there a
nd they asked me to become a Sunday school teacher, I don't know what qualifications I had but I was well up in religious knowledge in those days. I won a prize from the Religious Tract Society and then I used to take the little children there is the grou
n
d floor in one of those little turnings off, you know Seven Dials, you know Seven Dials, well one of those three turnings, I used to go there around Better ton Street a squalid part of and quite a lot of those children they used to break my heart when you
 asked if they'd had any dinner, perhaps some of them hardly had a little something about I was perhaps 18 or 19 attached to the London Medical mission, of course I don't know what happened I gave up here after a time. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5243694\charrsid4274267 There was a lot of squalor in those days.
